window.MODULES=window.MODULES||{};window.MODULES["mechanical-circulatory-support"]={"slug": "mechanical-circulatory-support", "title": "Mechanical Circulatory Support", "tagline": "A device-by-device fellowship reference: IABP, Impella, TandemHeart, VA-ECMO, and durable LVADs — physiology, alarms, troubleshooting, and the trials that shaped practice.", "level": 3, "readMin": 62, "takeaways": ["Match the device to the failing chamber and the goal: IABP augments diastolic coronary perfusion and afterload-reduces (modest ~0.5 L/min support); Impella and TandemHeart directly unload the LV with 2.5-5.5 L/min; VA-ECMO oxygenates and supports both ventricles but INCREASES LV afterload; durable LVADs are the destination/bridge continuous-flow solution.", "The three landmark shock trials define the evidence: IABP-SHOCK II (no mortality benefit from routine IABP in AMI shock), DanGer Shock (microaxial flow pump reduced 180-day mortality in STEMI shock at a cost of more complications), and ECLS-SHOCK (routine early VA-ECMO gave no mortality benefit with more bleeding/ischemia).", "VA-ECMO's central problem is LV distension from retrograde aortic flow meeting a weak ventricle: watch for a flat arterial line, rising PCWP/pulmonary edema, and stagnant blood risking thrombus — vent the LV (Impella 'ECPELLA', IABP, atrial septostomy, or surgical vent) when it distends.", "North-South (Harlequin) syndrome is differential hypoxia from peripheral VA-ECMO: well-oxygenated pump blood perfuses the lower body while poorly oxygenated blood from failing native lungs and a recovering heart perfuses the head and right arm — monitor the RIGHT radial ABG and SpO2.", "Impella troubleshooting hinges on reading placement signal, motor current, and suction alarms together: a suction alarm plus loss of the pulsatile placement waveform usually means the inlet is against the LV wall or the LV is underfilled (RV failure, tamponade, hypovolemia) — reduce P-level and give volume before assuming malposition.", "Durable HeartMate 3 physiology is preload-dependent and afterload-sensitive: low flow with low pulsatility index suggests hypovolemia, RV failure, or tamponade; a suction event with a low PI alarm means the inflow cannula collapsed the LV — reduce speed and resuscitate volume."], "sections": [{"id": "overview", "title": "Framework: Matching Device to Physiology", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Mechanical circulatory support (MCS) is not a single therapy but a family of pumps that fail for different reasons and support different chambers. The single most important cognitive step before touching any device is to answer three questions: <strong>Which ventricle is failing?</strong> <strong>Do I need oxygenation or only flow?</strong> and <strong>What is the exit strategy (recovery, transplant, durable device, or withdrawal)?</strong> Every downstream decision follows from these."}, {"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Broadly, temporary MCS spans a spectrum of support magnitude and complexity: the intra-aortic balloon pump (IABP) provides modest augmentation (~0.3-0.5 L/min equivalent) through counterpulsation; percutaneous ventricular assist devices (Impella, TandemHeart) directly unload a ventricle and deliver 2.5-5.5 L/min; and veno-arterial extracorporeal membrane oxygenation (VA-ECMO) provides full cardiopulmonary support with gas exchange. Durable LVADs (HeartMate 3) are surgically implanted continuous-flow pumps for months to years."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 1, "entries": [{"term": "Counterpulsation", "def": "Inflating a device in diastole and deflating in systole to raise diastolic (coronary perfusion) pressure and lower systolic afterload. The mechanism of the IABP."}, {"term": "Ventricular unloading", "def": "Actively removing blood from a ventricle to reduce its volume, wall stress, and myocardial oxygen demand. Impella and TandemHeart unload directly; VA-ECMO does NOT unload the LV and may worsen its loading."}, {"term": "Bridge to recovery (BTR)", "def": "Temporary support with the expectation of native myocardial recovery (e.g., fulminant myocarditis, post-cardiotomy stunning)."}, {"term": "Bridge to decision / bridge to bridge", "def": "Stabilize a patient in extremis while candidacy for transplant or durable device is determined, or while transferring to a durable device."}, {"term": "Bridge to transplant (BTT) / Destination therapy (DT)", "def": "Durable LVAD indications: BTT for transplant candidates; DT for patients ineligible for transplant who will keep the device permanently."}]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "label": "Device comparison at a glance", "head": ["Device", "Chamber supported", "Typical flow", "Oxygenation?", "Effect on LV afterload", "Access"], "rows": [["IABP", "LV (indirect)", "~0.3-0.5 L/min equiv.", "No", "Decreases (afterload reduction)", "7.5-8 Fr femoral (or axillary)"], ["Impella CP", "LV", "~3.7 L/min", "No", "Decreases (direct unloading)", "14 Fr femoral/axillary"], ["Impella 5.5", "LV", "~5.5 L/min", "No", "Decreases", "Surgical axillary cutdown"], ["Impella RP", "RV", "~4 L/min", "No", "n/a (RV support)", "23 Fr femoral vein"], ["TandemHeart", "LV (LA-to-artery)", "~4-5 L/min", "No (unless oxygenator added)", "Decreases LV preload", "21 Fr venous + transseptal"], ["VA-ECMO", "Both (LV+RV) + lungs", "4-6+ L/min", "Yes", "INCREASES (retrograde aortic flow)", "Venous + arterial cannulae"], ["HeartMate 3 (durable)", "LV", "4-6 L/min", "No", "Decreases", "Surgical, intrapericardial"]]}, {"type": "callout", "depth": 2, "variant": "fellow", "text": "<strong>The afterload paradox of VA-ECMO.</strong> Unlike every other left-sided device, VA-ECMO pumps oxygenated blood <em>retrograde</em> up the aorta, raising the pressure the failing LV must eject against. A stunned LV may be unable to open the aortic valve at all, leading to blood stasis, LV distension, pulmonary edema, and intracardiac thrombus. This is why LV venting is a central preoccupation of ECMO management and why it is discussed in its own section below."}, {"type": "callout", "depth": 1, "variant": "pearl", "text": "<strong>Mnemonic — pick your pump with 'FLOW':</strong> <strong>F</strong>ailing chamber (L, R, or both?), <strong>L</strong>ung function (need oxygenation? then ECMO), <strong>O</strong>utflow needed (how many L/min?), <strong>W</strong>hat's the exit (recovery, transplant, durable, or palliation?)."}]}, {"id": "shock-physiology", "title": "Cardiogenic Shock: The Substrate for MCS", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Cardiogenic shock (CS) is a state of end-organ hypoperfusion caused by primary cardiac failure. It is defined hemodynamically by a cardiac index typically below 1.8-2.2 L/min/m2 (without or with support), a systolic BP under 90 mmHg for more than 30 minutes or vasopressor requirement, and elevated filling pressures (PCWP typically >15 mmHg), accompanied by clinical or biochemical hypoperfusion (oliguria, cool extremities, lactate >2 mmol/L)."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "label": "SCAI SHOCK stages (2019, revised 2022)", "head": ["Stage", "Label", "Description", "Typical bedside"], "rows": [["A", "At risk", "No current shock but at risk (e.g., large anterior STEMI)", "Normal exam, normal lactate"], ["B", "Beginning", "Compensated: hypotension or tachycardia without hypoperfusion", "Low BP, warm, lactate normal, JVD"], ["C", "Classic", "Hypoperfusion requiring intervention (inotrope/pressor/MCS)", "Cool, oliguria, lactate >2, needs support"], ["D", "Deteriorating", "Failing to respond, needs escalation", "Worsening on initial support"], ["E", "Extremis", "Circulatory collapse, refractory arrest", "CPR, near-death, profound acidosis"]]}, {"type": "callout", "depth": 2, "variant": "fellow", "text": "The SCAI stage should be reassessed frequently and paired with a modifier for cardiac arrest. A patient can move up or down stages; escalation of MCS is driven by trajectory (rising lactate, rising pressor dose) at least as much as by any single number. The concept of the 'hub-and-spoke' shock team and early right-heart catheterization to phenotype shock (wet/dry, warm/cold, LV/RV/biventricular) is now standard of care."}, {"type": "p", "depth": 3, "text": "Right-heart catheterization phenotyping directs device choice. A high PCWP with preserved RA pressure and adequate PAPi suggests isolated LV failure amenable to LV support. A low PAPi (<1.0-1.85 depending on context), high RA/PCWP ratio (>0.63), and RV dilation flag RV failure that will worsen or become unmasked when an LV device increases venous return. Placing an Impella CP into a patient with occult RV failure and expecting the flows to appear is a classic trap: the LV device is preload-starved because the RV cannot deliver blood across the lungs."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 3, "entries": [{"term": "PAPi (pulmonary artery pulsatility index)", "def": "(PA systolic - PA diastolic) / RA pressure. Low values (roughly <1.0 in acute MI, <1.85 in other contexts) predict RV failure and need for RV support."}, {"term": "Cardiac power output (CPO)", "def": "(MAP x CO) / 451, in watts. CPO <0.6 W is a strong predictor of mortality in cardiogenic shock and a trigger to consider escalation."}]}, {"type": "callout", "depth": 1, "variant": "pearl", "text": "<strong>Mnemonic — the shock team's 'PALM' before escalating MCS:</strong> <strong>P</strong>erfusion (lactate, urine, mentation), <strong>A</strong>fterload (SVR, is this vasodilatory overlap?), <strong>L</strong>eft vs right (which ventricle?), <strong>M</strong>etabolics/reversibility (can this recover?)."}]}, {"id": "iabp", "title": "Intra-Aortic Balloon Pump (IABP)", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "The IABP is a polyethylene balloon (typically 30-50 mL, most often 40 mL in adults) mounted on a catheter positioned in the descending thoracic aorta, with its tip just distal to the left subclavian artery (roughly at the level of the carina on chest film) and above the renal arteries. It inflates with helium during diastole and deflates just before systole. Helium is used because its low density permits rapid shuttling."}, {"type": "figure", "depth": 1, "src": "../assets/fig/iabp-balloon.png", "alt": "Intra-aortic balloon pump catheter with balloon inflated in the descending thoracic aorta", "caption": "IABP catheter in the descending thoracic aorta, tip just distal to the left subclavian. Diastolic inflation augments coronary perfusion; presystolic deflation drops afterload.", "credit": "BruceBlaus — CC BY-SA 4.0, via Wikimedia Commons", "source": "https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Intraaortic_Balloon.png"}, {"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Two effects define its benefit. <strong>Diastolic augmentation:</strong> balloon inflation at the dicrotic notch displaces blood, raising aortic diastolic pressure and thereby coronary perfusion pressure. <strong>Systolic unloading:</strong> rapid deflation immediately before the aortic valve opens creates a brief pressure void, reducing the afterload the LV ejects against, lowering myocardial oxygen demand and modestly increasing stroke volume and cardiac output (~0.5 L/min)."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 1, "entries": [{"term": "Counterpulsation timing", "def": "Inflation is triggered at the dicrotic notch (aortic valve closure) and deflation at end-diastole, just before the next systole. Triggering is most often ECG-gated (to the R wave) or pressure-gated."}, {"term": "Augmentation", "def": "The peak diastolic pressure generated by balloon inflation. On a properly timed 1:2 tracing, the augmented diastolic peak should exceed the patient's own systolic peak."}, {"term": "1:1, 1:2, 1:3 ratio", "def": "The frequency of assist relative to cardiac cycles. 1:2 (every other beat) is used to assess timing because assisted and unassisted beats can be compared side by side; weaning is done by reducing the ratio."}]}, {"type": "figure", "depth": 2, "caption": "The idealized IABP arterial waveform on a 1:2 tracing shows, in order: the unassisted systolic peak, the dicrotic notch, the augmented diastolic peak (higher than the unassisted systole), a reduced assisted aortic end-diastolic pressure (lower than the unassisted end-diastole), and a reduced next assisted systole. Learning to read this tracing is how timing errors are diagnosed.", "alt": "Schematic of an IABP-assisted arterial pressure waveform showing diastolic augmentation and systolic unloading"}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "label": "IABP timing errors — recognition and consequence", "head": ["Error", "What happens", "Waveform clue", "Consequence"], "rows": [["Early inflation", "Balloon inflates before aortic valve closes", "Augmentation encroaches on/before the dicrotic notch", "Premature aortic valve closure, increased LVEDV/afterload, regurgitation"], ["Late inflation", "Inflates well after the dicrotic notch", "Augmentation appears after the notch, absent sharp V", "Suboptimal coronary augmentation"], ["Early deflation", "Deflates too soon in diastole", "Sharp drop then rise before next systole (U shape)", "Loss of afterload reduction, possible retrograde coronary flow, no benefit"], ["Late deflation", "Deflates after systole begins", "Widened, prolonged augmentation; assisted systole delayed/blunted", "Increased afterload, impeded LV ejection — the most dangerous error"]]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "label": "IABP alarms — situation / cause / treatment", "head": ["Alarm / situation", "Likely cause", "Action"], "rows": [["Loss of augmentation / low augmentation", "Balloon too low, hypovolemia, tachyarrhythmia, catheter kink", "Check position on CXR, assess volume, correct rhythm, inspect tubing"], ["Gas leak / blood in catheter", "Balloon perforation (helium loss, risk of gas embolism)", "STOP pumping immediately, clamp, remove balloon urgently — do not attempt to restart"], ["Trigger loss", "Poor ECG signal, arrhythmia, pacing spikes miscounted", "Switch trigger source (ECG to pressure), improve lead contact"], ["Rapid gas loss / autofill failure", "Small leak or high heart rate outstripping shuttle", "Reduce assist ratio, evaluate for leak, refill helium"], ["Reduced/absent left arm pulse or new neuro deficit", "Balloon migrated proximally, occluding subclavian/carotid", "Reposition — pull back; urgent imaging"]]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "label": "IABP indications and contraindications", "head": ["Indications", "Absolute contraindications", "Relative contraindications"], "rows": [["Refractory ischemia / bridge to revascularization", "Significant aortic regurgitation (augmentation worsens AR)", "Uncontrolled sepsis"], ["Cardiogenic shock as adjunct (selected)", "Aortic dissection", "Severe peripheral arterial disease"], ["Mechanical complications of MI (acute MR, VSD) as bridge to surgery", "Aortic aneurysm (large/rupture risk)", "Severe aortoiliac atherosclerosis / small vessels"], ["Refractory ventricular arrhythmias from ischemia", "", "Uncontrolled coagulopathy"], ["High-risk PCI support (selected)", "", ""]]}, {"type": "callout", "depth": 2, "variant": "danger", "text": "<strong>Significant aortic regurgitation is an absolute contraindication.</strong> Diastolic balloon inflation increases the regurgitant volume and LV filling, worsening pulmonary edema and defeating the entire purpose. <strong>Aortic dissection</strong> is equally prohibited — the balloon can extend the dissection or be placed in a false lumen. Always exclude both before insertion."}, {"type": "list", "depth": 2, "label": "IABP complications", "items": ["Limb ischemia (most common vascular complication) from the large arterial sheath — check distal pulses hourly", "Balloon rupture with helium gas embolism (rare but catastrophic)", "Thrombocytopenia (mechanical platelet consumption) and hemolysis", "Aortic injury, dissection, or visceral/spinal ischemia from malposition", "Infection at the access site; bleeding", "Balloon entrapment (failure to deflate, adherent thrombus) requiring surgical removal"]}, {"type": "callout", "depth": 3, "variant": "fellow", "text": "<strong>IABP-SHOCK II</strong> randomized 600 patients with acute MI complicated by cardiogenic shock and planned early revascularization to IABP versus none. There was <strong>no difference in 30-day mortality</strong> (roughly 40% in both arms), and this held out to 6-year follow-up. The trial fundamentally changed practice: routine IABP in AMI shock is not recommended and carries a Class III recommendation in that specific setting. The IABP retains a niche role in mechanical complications (acute severe MR, post-MI VSD) as a bridge to surgery, and in refractory ischemia, where afterload reduction and coronary augmentation are directly beneficial."}, {"type": "linkout", "depth": 1, "text": "Review the classic IABP arterial waveform, dicrotic notch timing, and the appearance of the four timing errors. A well-annotated waveform is worth more than any verbal description for building pattern recognition.", "url": "https://litfl.com/ecg-library/", "label": "LITFL library (waveform reference)"}]}, {"id": "impella", "title": "Impella: Axial-Flow Ventricular Support", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "The Impella is a catheter-mounted, transvalvular axial-flow (Archimedes screw) pump. For LV support, the inlet sits in the LV cavity and the outlet in the ascending aorta above the aortic valve; the impeller continuously aspirates blood from the LV and expels it into the aorta. This <strong>directly unloads the LV</strong> — reducing LV volume, wall stress, myocardial oxygen demand, and PCWP — while increasing systemic forward flow. Unlike the IABP, it does not depend on native LV function or timing."}, {"type": "figure", "depth": 1, "src": "../assets/fig/mcs-pv-unloaded.png", "alt": "Pressure-volume loops showing baseline versus mechanically unloaded left ventricle", "caption": "LV pressure–volume loops: active unloading (green) shifts the loop down and left of baseline (red), cutting wall stress and myocardial O₂ demand — the hemodynamic goal of Impella support.", "credit": "Skire913 — CC BY-SA 4.0, via Wikimedia Commons", "source": "https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:PV_Loop_loaded_vs._unloaded.png"}, {"type": "linkout", "depth": 1, "label": "Impella — device overview", "text": "Impella is proprietary (Abiomed); no openly-licensed device photo exists — see the encyclopedic device overview", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Impella"}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "label": "Impella family", "head": ["Device", "Max flow", "Motor size / access", "Role"], "rows": [["Impella 2.5", "~2.5 L/min", "12 Fr / femoral percutaneous", "High-risk PCI support (largely superseded by CP)"], ["Impella CP", "~3.7 L/min", "14 Fr / femoral or axillary", "Cardiogenic shock, high-risk PCI (workhorse)"], ["Impella 5.0", "~5.0 L/min", "21 Fr / surgical (axillary or femoral cutdown)", "Higher, durable support; ambulation possible"], ["Impella 5.5", "~5.5 L/min", "Surgical axillary cutdown", "Bridge to recovery/decision/transplant; weeks of support"], ["Impella RP / RP Flex", "~4.0 L/min", "23 Fr femoral vein (RP); RP Flex designed for right internal jugular access", "RV support: inflow in IVC, outflow in PA; RP Flex frees the groin for ambulation"]]}, {"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Support is set by <strong>P-levels</strong> (P-0 to P-8/P-9 depending on device), which correspond to defined pump speeds and therefore flow. The controller displays flow, motor current, and a placement signal, and these three readouts together are how the pump is monitored and troubleshot."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 2, "entries": [{"term": "P-level", "def": "Performance level = a preset motor speed (RPM) and thus target flow. Higher P-level = higher speed = more flow and more unloading, but greater suction risk if the LV is underfilled."}, {"term": "Motor current", "def": "The current the motor draws to spin the impeller at the set speed. It is pulsatile in normal positioning because the pressure difference across the impeller changes through the cardiac cycle. A flat, non-pulsatile motor current suggests the inlet and outlet are on the same side of the aortic valve (malposition) or continuous suction."}, {"term": "Placement signal", "def": "The pressure waveform sensed at the pump. Correct LV positioning shows a ventricular (pulsatile, low-diastolic) waveform at the inlet region; an aortic waveform where a ventricular one is expected means the inlet has slipped across the valve into the aorta."}, {"term": "Purge system", "def": "A pressurized dextrose (typically 5-40% dextrose, often with heparin) solution continuously infused through the motor to prevent blood from entering and clotting the bearings. Purge pressure and flow are monitored; a rising purge pressure suggests thrombus formation in the purge path."}]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "label": "Impella alarms — situation / cause / treatment", "head": ["Alarm", "Cause", "Action"], "rows": [["Suction alarm", "Inlet obstructed: LV underfilled (hypovolemia, RV failure, tamponade), or inlet against LV wall/septum, or position too deep", "Reduce P-level, give volume, echo to check position and RV; reposition if wall-apposed"], ["Impella position wrong / needs repositioning", "Migration across aortic valve (inlet in aorta, or too deep in LV)", "Bedside echo; reposition under imaging to restore inlet ~3.5 cm below the valve"], ["Low purge pressure", "Purge line disconnect/leak, low cassette volume", "Inspect purge circuit, increase purge concentration/rate per protocol"], ["High purge pressure", "Thrombus forming in the purge path / kinked line", "Check for kink; rising trend may mandate purge concentration change or device exchange"], ["Low flow / flow lower than expected", "Underfilling, high afterload, malposition, or hemolysis-related", "Assess volume and RV, check position, evaluate for suction"], ["Controller: 'Impella Stopped'", "Motor stopped (thrombus, kink, air)", "Emergent troubleshooting; may need restart or exchange — do not leave stopped (thrombosis/regurgitation risk)"]]}, {"type": "steps", "depth": 2, "label": "Troubleshooting the suction alarm (the most common bedside call)", "items": ["Look at the three signals together: suction alarm + damped/flattened placement waveform + falling flow = the inlet is not getting blood.", "First reduce the P-level by 1-2 steps to lower the aspiration demand.", "Assess volume status: give a fluid bolus if the patient is hypovolemic (a preload-dependent axial pump cannot pump an empty ventricle).", "Get a focused echo: is the inlet against the lateral wall or septum? Is the LV small and hyperdynamic? Is there tamponade or new RV failure?", "If the RV has failed, the LV is preload-starved — the fix is RV support (Impella RP, inotropes, pulmonary vasodilators), not more LV speed.", "Reposition the catheter under echo/fluoroscopy if wall-apposed or malpositioned; only then return P-level toward target."]}, {"type": "callout", "depth": 3, "variant": "fellow", "text": "<strong>Hemolysis</strong> is the signature Impella complication. The high shear of the axial impeller can shear red cells, especially with suction, malposition (inlet near the wall), or high speeds. Watch for rising plasma-free hemoglobin, rising LDH, falling haptoglobin, hemoglobinuria (pink/tea-colored urine), and a falling hematocrit. Management: correct suction and malposition first (echo-guided repositioning, reduce P-level, optimize volume), then reassess. Persistent severe hemolysis despite optimization may require device exchange or removal. Hemolysis also drives AKI and can confound the picture with concurrent GI bleeding on anticoagulation."}, {"type": "callout", "depth": 2, "variant": "danger", "text": "<strong>Contraindications:</strong> mechanical aortic valve (the catheter crosses the valve), significant aortic stenosis or moderate-or-worse aortic regurgitation, LV thrombus (embolization risk), severe peripheral arterial disease precluding access, and a known ventricular septal defect (LV unloading can worsen right-to-left shunting). Aortic regurgitation is worsened because the transvalvular device holds the valve open."}, {"type": "list", "depth": 2, "label": "Additional Impella complications", "items": ["Vascular/limb ischemia and access-site bleeding (large-bore arterial access)", "Aortic valve injury or worsening AR from the transvalvular catheter", "Device migration requiring repositioning", "Thrombosis/stroke; purge-system thrombosis", "Right ventricular failure unmasked by increased LV output demand"]}, {"type": "callout", "depth": 3, "variant": "fellow", "text": "<strong>DanGer Shock</strong> (2024) is the first randomized trial to show a mortality benefit for a microaxial flow pump in STEMI-related cardiogenic shock. Routine use of the Impella CP reduced 180-day all-cause mortality compared with standard care (roughly 46% vs 58%, hazard ratio ~0.74), a meaningful absolute reduction, but at the cost of significantly more adverse events — severe bleeding, limb ischemia, hemolysis, and renal replacement therapy. Importantly, the trial enrolled STEMI-shock patients and <em>excluded comatose out-of-hospital cardiac arrest survivors</em>, so the benefit applies to a selected population managed by experienced teams. The lesson for the fellow is nuanced: early LV unloading can save lives, but it is not free — it demands vigilant management of exactly the complications catalogued above. This is a sharp contrast with the negative IABP-SHOCK II and ECLS-SHOCK results and has reshaped shock algorithms."}, {"type": "callout", "depth": 1, "variant": "pearl", "text": "<strong>Mnemonic — Impella suction is 'SUCK':</strong> <strong>S</strong>peed too high (reduce P-level), <strong>U</strong>nderfilled ventricle (give volume), <strong>C</strong>atheter against wall (reposition on echo), <strong>K</strong>illed RV (right heart failed — support the RV)."}, {"type": "linkout", "depth": 1, "text": "Review the chest radiograph and echocardiographic appearance of a correctly positioned Impella (inlet ~3.5 cm below the aortic annulus, pigtail in the LV) versus malposition.", "url": "https://radiopaedia.org/", "label": "Radiopaedia (device positioning imaging)"}]}, {"id": "tandemheart", "title": "TandemHeart: Trans-Septal Left Atrial Bypass", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "The TandemHeart is an extracorporeal centrifugal pump that provides left atrial-to-arterial bypass. A 21 Fr inflow cannula is placed via the femoral vein and advanced across the interatrial septum (requiring transseptal puncture) into the <strong>left atrium</strong>; oxygenated blood is withdrawn from the LA, passed through an external centrifugal pump, and returned to the arterial system through a femoral arterial cannula. It can deliver 4-5 L/min."}, {"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Because it draws from the left atrium and bypasses the LV entirely, it reduces LV preload and PCWP and augments systemic flow. It does not require crossing the aortic valve, so it can be used when a transvalvular device is contraindicated (e.g., mechanical aortic valve), but it demands operator skill in transseptal puncture and carries the specific risks of that procedure."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 2, "entries": [{"term": "Transseptal cannulation", "def": "The inflow cannula must cross the interatrial septum to reach the LA. Inadvertent dislodgement of the cannula back into the RA causes a large left-to-right shunt and precipitous desaturation/hemodynamic collapse."}, {"term": "LA-to-femoral-artery circuit", "def": "The defining configuration: preload is drawn from the LA, so the LV is unloaded at the level of its inflow rather than transvalvularly."}]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "label": "TandemHeart — indications, contraindications, complications", "head": ["Indications", "Contraindications", "Complications"], "rows": [["Cardiogenic shock needing 4-5 L/min", "Ventricular septal defect (shunt)", "Cannula migration to RA with right-to-left/left-to-right shunt and desaturation"], ["High-risk PCI when a transvalvular device is unsuitable", "Severe peripheral arterial disease (large arterial cannula)", "Transseptal complications: tamponade, aortic puncture"], ["Bridge to decision", "Right ventricular failure (LA drainage worsens forward RV demand mismatch)", "Limb ischemia, bleeding, thrombosis, hemolysis"], ["Can be configured for RV support (RA-to-PA) or with an oxygenator", "Coagulopathy / contraindication to anticoagulation", "Air embolism, stroke"]]}, {"type": "callout", "depth": 3, "variant": "fellow", "text": "The TandemHeart has largely been displaced by the Impella and VA-ECMO in many centers because of the complexity of transseptal cannulation and cannula management, but it remains valuable in specific scenarios: when the aortic valve cannot be crossed, and in dedicated configurations (RA-to-PA for RV support). The ProtekDuo dual-lumen cannula, placed via the internal jugular vein with drainage from the RA and return to the PA, is a percutaneous RV support option that can be paired with an oxygenator (oxy-RVAD)."}]}, {"id": "va-ecmo", "title": "VA-ECMO: Full Cardiopulmonary Support", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Veno-arterial ECMO is the most powerful temporary MCS: it drains deoxygenated blood from the venous system, passes it through a membrane oxygenator (gas exchange) and a centrifugal pump, and returns oxygenated blood to the arterial system. It supports <strong>both ventricles and the lungs</strong> simultaneously, making it the device of choice for biventricular failure, refractory arrest (ECPR), and shock with concomitant respiratory failure or profound hypoxemia."}, {"type": "figure", "depth": 1, "src": "../assets/fig/va-ecmo-diagram.jpg", "alt": "Schematic of a veno-arterial ECMO circuit", "caption": "VA-ECMO circuit: venous blood is drained, oxygenated across the membrane, and returned to the arterial system — full cardiopulmonary support independent of native cardiac output.", "credit": "Van Meurs/Lally/Peek/Zwischenberger, ELSO — CC BY 2.5, via Wikimedia Commons", "source": "https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Veno-arterial_(VA)_ECMO_for_cardiac_or_respiratory_failure.jpg"}, {"type": "figure", "depth": 1, "src": "../assets/fig/ecmo-console.jpg", "alt": "Bedside ECMO console with centrifugal pump, membrane oxygenator and blood tubing", "caption": "The real hardware: a bedside ECMO console — centrifugal pump, membrane oxygenator (Quadrox), blood lines, and patient monitor at left.", "credit": "Cmenesesoliveira — Public domain, via Wikimedia Commons", "source": "https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:ECMO_in_H1N1_patient_in_Santa_Cruz_Hospital_-_Lisbon.jpg"}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "label": "VA-ECMO cannulation configurations", "head": ["Config", "Drainage / return", "Flow direction", "Notes"], "rows": [["Peripheral femoral-femoral", "Femoral vein (RA) → femoral artery", "Retrograde up the aorta", "Fastest to place; causes differential hypoxia and increased LV afterload"], ["Peripheral with distal perfusion", "Adds antegrade catheter to the leg", "As above", "Prevents limb ischemia in the cannulated leg"], ["Central", "RA → ascending aorta (open chest)", "Antegrade", "Post-cardiotomy; avoids differential hypoxia but is a surgical open-chest circuit"], ["Axillary/subclavian arterial return", "Vein → axillary artery", "More antegrade", "Reduces differential hypoxia; risk of arm hyperperfusion"]]}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 2, "entries": [{"term": "Sweep gas", "def": "The fresh gas flowing across the oxygenator membrane. It controls CO2 removal: increasing sweep lowers PaCO2. It is set independently of blood flow (which, with FiO2, controls oxygenation)."}, {"term": "Blood flow (pump flow)", "def": "Set by centrifugal pump RPM; the primary determinant of oxygen delivery and systemic support. Limited by drainage (preload to the circuit)."}, {"term": "Chatter / suck-down", "def": "Cannula line vibration from over-drainage against an underfilled venous system — analogous to suction. Reduce flow and give volume."}]}, {"type": "callout", "depth": 2, "variant": "danger", "text": "<strong>North-South (Harlequin / differential hypoxia) syndrome.</strong> In peripheral femoral VA-ECMO with recovering native cardiac output but failing lungs, the heart ejects <em>poorly oxygenated</em> blood forward that perfuses the upper body (coronaries, right arm, brain), while the ECMO circuit's <em>well-oxygenated</em> retrograde flow perfuses the lower body. The watershed 'mixing point' sits somewhere in the aorta. The result is a cyanotic upper body ('north') and a pink lower body ('south'). <strong>Always monitor the RIGHT radial arterial line and right-hand SpO2</strong> — these reflect the least-oxygenated territory (coronary and cerebral). Treat by improving native lung oxygenation, adding a return limb higher up (V-A-V hybrid), or switching to central/axillary return."}, {"type": "callout", "depth": 2, "variant": "danger", "text": "<strong>LV distension and the need for venting.</strong> Retrograde aortic flow raises LV afterload. If the LV is too weak to open the aortic valve against this pressure, blood stagnates in the LV and LA, causing rising LVEDP, pulmonary edema (a classic 'white-out' on CXR), and stasis-related intracardiac thrombus. Signs: loss of arterial pulsatility (a flat, non-pulsatile arterial line), rising PCWP, worsening pulmonary edema, and on echo a dilated LV with a closed aortic valve and spontaneous echo contrast ('smoke')."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "label": "LV venting strategies on VA-ECMO", "head": ["Strategy", "Mechanism", "Notes"], "rows": [["Impella + VA-ECMO ('ECPELLA')", "Impella actively unloads the LV while ECMO supports flow/oxygenation", "Increasingly favored; two large-bore accesses, additive complications"], ["IABP", "Afterload reduction improves LV emptying, restores some pulsatility", "Weakest venting but simple; may not fully decompress"], ["Atrial septostomy / trans-septal LA drain", "Decompresses the LA directly", "Percutaneous; effective LA decompression"], ["Surgical LV vent / pulmonary artery vent", "Direct mechanical decompression", "Requires surgical access; used in central ECMO"], ["Inotropes", "Improve intrinsic LV ejection to open the aortic valve", "Adjunct; increases myocardial oxygen demand"]]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "label": "VA-ECMO alarms/emergencies — situation / cause / treatment", "head": ["Situation", "Cause", "Action"], "rows": [["Line chatter / suck-down, low flow", "Hypovolemia, cannula malposition, tamponade", "Reduce RPM, volume bolus, echo for tamponade/position"], ["Sudden loss of flow, air in circuit", "Air entrainment (venous line), circuit disruption", "Clamp, place patient on manual support, de-air, emergent perfusion team"], ["Rising pre-oxygenator pressure / high dP across oxygenator", "Oxygenator clot/failure", "Prepare for oxygenator/circuit exchange"], ["Rising PaCO2 or falling PaO2 despite flow", "Oxygenator failure or wet lung (condensate)", "Increase sweep (CO2), check for oxygenator failure, flush/replace"], ["Falling right-radial SpO2 with good lower-body sats", "North-South / differential hypoxia", "Optimize native lung, consider V-A-V or axillary return"], ["Flat arterial line + pulmonary edema", "LV distension", "Institute LV venting (see table above)"], ["Cold, pulseless cannulated limb", "Distal limb ischemia", "Place distal perfusion cannula urgently"]]}, {"type": "steps", "depth": 3, "label": "VA-ECMO weaning trial", "items": ["Confirm recovery signs: improving pulse pressure/pulsatility, improving LV function on echo, low/absent lactate, low vasopressor need.", "Ensure the lungs are adequate (native oxygenation acceptable) and rhythm/volume are optimized.", "Reduce pump flow stepwise (e.g., to ~1.0-1.5 L/min minimum to avoid circuit thrombosis, often with additional anticoagulation for the low-flow trial).", "At low flow, reassess hemodynamics and echo: adequate MAP, cardiac index, and LV/RV function with tolerable filling pressures indicates readiness.", "If the trial is tolerated, decannulate (surgical repair of the arteriotomy is usually required for large cannulae).", "If not tolerated, return to full support and reassess for durable device or transplant candidacy."]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "label": "VA-ECMO indications and contraindications", "head": ["Indications", "Absolute contraindications", "Relative contraindications"], "rows": [["Refractory cardiogenic shock (any cause), biventricular failure", "Unrecoverable cardiac disease without transplant/durable option", "Advanced age, severe comorbidity"], ["ECPR for refractory cardiac arrest (selected)", "Severe aortic regurgitation, aortic dissection", "Prolonged CPR/no-flow, established multi-organ failure"], ["Massive PE with shock; poisoning/overdose with cardiotoxicity", "Contraindication to anticoagulation (relative to absolute if severe)", "Severe peripheral arterial disease"], ["Bridge to decision/transplant/durable LVAD; peri-procedural support", "Prolonged anoxic brain injury", "Aortic disease limiting cannulation"]]}, {"type": "callout", "depth": 3, "variant": "fellow", "text": "<strong>ECLS-SHOCK</strong> (2023) randomized about 420 patients with acute MI complicated by cardiogenic shock to early routine VA-ECMO versus standard care. There was <strong>no reduction in 30-day mortality</strong> (roughly 48% in both arms) and significantly more bleeding and peripheral vascular ischemic complications in the ECMO arm. Combined with prior meta-analytic data, this argues against reflexive early ECMO in AMI shock. ECMO remains indispensable for specific indications — biventricular collapse, refractory arrest with a reversible cause, respiratory failure with shock — but the trial reinforces that the device does not itself confer survival unless it bridges to something (recovery, durable device, transplant) and its complication burden is substantial."}, {"type": "linkout", "depth": 1, "text": "Review chest radiographs of VA-ECMO cannula positioning and the 'white-out' pulmonary edema of LV distension, and cannula-related complications.", "url": "https://radiopaedia.org/", "label": "Radiopaedia (ECMO imaging)"}]}, {"id": "rv-support", "title": "Isolated Right Ventricular Support", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "RV failure — from RV infarction, acute PE, post-LVAD RV failure, or pulmonary hypertension crisis — is under-recognized and lethal. The failing RV is preload-dependent yet exquisitely afterload-sensitive; the management principles are to optimize preload (neither dry nor overloaded), reduce RV afterload (treat hypoxia, hypercarbia, acidosis; pulmonary vasodilators), support contractility (inotropes), and maintain coronary perfusion (avoid systemic hypotension). When medical therapy fails, mechanical RV support is indicated."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "label": "Percutaneous RV support options", "head": ["Device", "Configuration", "Flow", "Notes"], "rows": [["Impella RP / RP Flex", "Inflow in IVC/RA, outflow in PA (across the tricuspid and pulmonic valves)", "~4 L/min", "Single venous access; do not use with mechanical tricuspid/pulmonic valves; RP Flex allows jugular access and ambulation"], ["ProtekDuo (RA-PA cannula) + pump", "Dual-lumen IJ cannula, drain RA return to PA, external centrifugal pump", "Up to ~4-5 L/min", "Can add oxygenator (oxy-RVAD); IJ access frees the groin and allows ambulation"], ["VA-ECMO", "Full biventricular + oxygenation", "4-6 L/min", "When RV failure coexists with LV failure or lung failure"]]}, {"type": "callout", "depth": 2, "variant": "fellow", "text": "Post-LVAD RV failure is a defining fellowship concept: implanting an LVAD increases venous return to a marginal RV while also shifting the interventricular septum leftward (removing septal contribution to RV output). This is why preoperative RV assessment (PAPi, RA/PCWP ratio, RV function) is central to durable LVAD candidacy — an occult failing RV predicts postoperative RVAD need and worse outcomes."}, {"type": "callout", "depth": 1, "variant": "pearl", "text": "<strong>Mnemonic — treat the failing RV with the 'RV-POP' bundle:</strong> <strong>R</strong>ate/rhythm (maintain AV synchrony), <strong>V</strong>olume (optimize, don't flood), <strong>P</strong>ulmonary afterload down (oxygen, avoid acidosis/hypercarbia, inhaled pulmonary vasodilators), <strong>O</strong>utput support (inotropes), <strong>P</strong>erfusion pressure (vasopressor to protect RV coronary flow)."}]}, {"id": "durable-lvad", "title": "Durable LVAD: HeartMate 3", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "The HeartMate 3 is a fully magnetically levitated (bearingless) centrifugal continuous-flow LVAD. An inflow cannula sits in the LV apex, blood is pumped by a magnetically suspended rotor, and an outflow graft returns blood to the ascending aorta. A percutaneous <strong>driveline</strong> exits the abdominal wall to connect to an external controller and batteries. The magnetic levitation eliminates mechanical bearings (reducing shear and thrombosis), and the pump generates intrinsic artificial pulsatility by periodically modulating rotor speed, which reduces stasis."}, {"type": "figure", "depth": 1, "src": "../assets/fig/lvad-diagram.png", "alt": "Diagram of a durable left ventricular assist device with driveline and controller", "caption": "Durable LVAD: inflow cannula in the LV apex → pump → outflow graft to the ascending aorta, with a percutaneous driveline to the external controller and batteries.", "credit": "Madhero88 — CC BY-SA 3.0, via Wikimedia Commons", "source": "https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Ventricular_assist_device.png"}, {"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Because flow is continuous, most patients have a markedly reduced or absent palpable pulse; blood pressure is measured by Doppler (opening pressure approximates mean arterial pressure), with a target MAP typically 70-80 mmHg (and generally kept below 90 to reduce stroke and GI bleeding risk). Understanding the four displayed parameters is the core competency."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 1, "entries": [{"term": "Speed (RPM)", "def": "The only directly set parameter. It is fixed by the clinician; the pump does not auto-regulate to physiologic demand. HeartMate 3 runs roughly 5000-6000 RPM."}, {"term": "Flow (L/min)", "def": "An ESTIMATED value derived from power and speed — not a measured flow. It rises with higher speed, higher preload, and lower afterload. Because it is estimated, a spuriously high or low displayed flow can reflect a power abnormality (e.g., thrombus)."}, {"term": "Power (watts)", "def": "The actual electrical power the motor consumes. A sustained, unexplained rise in power (with a falsely elevated flow) is a red flag for pump thrombosis."}, {"term": "Pulsatility index (PI)", "def": "A measure of the magnitude of flow pulsations through the cardiac cycle, reflecting the difference between the LV's own contractility/preload and the pump. Higher PI = more native ventricular filling/contribution. A sudden drop in PI (PI event) signals reduced LV volume (suction)."}]}, {"type": "callout", "depth": 2, "variant": "fellow", "text": "<strong>Reading the parameters as a system.</strong> Continuous-flow LVADs are <em>preload-dependent and afterload-sensitive</em>. Low flow with a low PI points to inadequate LV filling — hypovolemia, RV failure, tamponade, or arrhythmia. Low flow with high power and a paradoxically high displayed flow suggests pump thrombosis. High flow with hypertension may reflect elevated afterload the pump is overcoming. Always integrate the four numbers rather than reacting to any single one, and confirm with echo and clinical exam."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "label": "HeartMate 3 alarms — situation / cause / treatment", "head": ["Alarm / pattern", "Cause", "Action"], "rows": [["Low flow alarm", "Hypovolemia, RV failure, tamponade, arrhythmia, hypertension (high afterload), inflow obstruction", "Assess volume, RV, rhythm, BP; echo; treat cause. Consider reducing speed if suction is driving it"], ["Suction event / low PI event", "Speed too high for LV volume; the inflow cannula collapses the underfilled LV against the cannula", "Reduce pump speed, give volume, treat arrhythmia; echo to confirm LV underfilling"], ["High power + falsely high displayed flow", "Pump thrombosis (clot increasing motor work)", "Check LDH/plasma-free Hgb, hemolysis labs, echo ramp study; escalate anticoagulation; may need pump exchange"], ["Low battery / controller alarm", "Power source depletion or connection fault", "Swap to fresh batteries / wall power; check driveline and controller connections"], ["Driveline damage / disconnection", "Cable fault or controller disconnect — can stop the pump", "Reconnect immediately; do NOT let the pump stop (regurgitation through the pump, thrombosis)"], ["Hazard/red alarm 'pump off'", "Pump stopped", "Emergently reconnect power/controller; a stopped LVAD is a life threat"]]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "label": "HeartMate 3 / durable LVAD complications", "head": ["Complication", "Mechanism", "Management principle"], "rows": [["GI bleeding / AV malformations", "Acquired von Willebrand syndrome (high-shear cleavage of large vWF multimers) + reduced pulsatility promoting angiodysplasia", "Endoscopy, reduce anticoagulation intensity, octreotide, minimize pulse pressure extremes"], ["Pump thrombosis", "Clot within the pump (much less common with HeartMate 3's mag-lev design)", "Hemolysis labs, ramp echo; intensify anticoagulation or pump exchange"], ["Driveline infection", "Percutaneous line breaches the skin barrier", "Local care, culture-directed antibiotics, immobilize driveline, surgical debridement if deep"], ["Stroke (ischemic or hemorrhagic)", "Thromboembolism, or hemorrhage from anticoagulation/high MAP", "Strict BP control (MAP <90), therapeutic INR, treat infection (raises stroke risk)"], ["RV failure", "Increased venous return + septal shift after LV unloading", "Optimize volume/afterload, inotropes, temporary RVAD if severe"], ["Aortic regurgitation (de novo)", "Continuous flow with an aortic valve that rarely opens leads to commissural fusion/AR over time", "Monitor by echo; may need intervention if severe"], ["Arrhythmias", "Suction events, scar, underlying cardiomyopathy", "Treat suction (reduce speed/volume), antiarrhythmics, ICD"]]}, {"type": "callout", "depth": 3, "variant": "fellow", "text": "<strong>MOMENTUM 3</strong> established the HeartMate 3 as the durable LVAD of choice: the fully magnetically levitated centrifugal pump markedly reduced pump thrombosis and disabling stroke compared with the older axial-flow HeartMate II, with superior survival free of disabling stroke or reoperation to replace the pump at 2 years. Pump thrombosis, historically the Achilles heel of continuous-flow LVADs, became rare. More recently, <strong>ARIES-HM3</strong> showed that omitting aspirin (maintaining vitamin K antagonist alone) in HeartMate 3 patients was non-inferior for thromboembolic events and reduced bleeding, so many centers now avoid aspirin. GI bleeding from acquired von Willebrand disease and angiodysplasia, driveline infection, and RV failure remain the dominant ongoing morbidities."}, {"type": "callout", "depth": 2, "variant": "danger", "text": "<strong>Cardiac arrest in an LVAD patient.</strong> Pulselessness is NORMAL in continuous-flow LVAD patients, so do not diagnose arrest by pulse. Assess mentation, capnography, Doppler, and the device (is it running? listen for the hum, check the controller). Chest compressions are given for true arrest with confirmed loss of perfusion and a pump not providing output, per current guidance, because withholding them in genuine arrest is fatal — but first exclude and correct a controller/power/driveline problem, which is often the actual cause."}, {"type": "callout", "depth": 1, "variant": "pearl", "text": "<strong>Mnemonic — the four LVAD numbers are 'S-Flo-P-PI':</strong> <strong>S</strong>peed is what YOU set, <strong>Flo</strong>w is ESTIMATED (don't trust it in isolation), <strong>P</strong>ower is what's really consumed (spikes = thrombus), <strong>PI</strong> reflects native filling (drops = suction/underfilled)."}, {"type": "linkout", "depth": 1, "text": "Review the chest radiograph of a HeartMate 3 (apical inflow cannula, pump body, outflow graft to the ascending aorta) and the echocardiographic ramp study used to evaluate pump thrombosis and speed optimization.", "url": "https://radiopaedia.org/", "label": "Radiopaedia (LVAD imaging)"}]}, {"id": "pharmacology", "title": "Pharmacology Around MCS", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Every MCS device sits within a pharmacologic envelope: anticoagulation to keep the circuit and pump patent, vasoactive support to maintain perfusion and drive intrinsic ventricular function, and pulmonary vasodilators for the failing RV. Doses below are standard adult starting points and must be titrated to the patient, the device protocol, and institutional practice."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "label": "Anticoagulation and antiplatelet agents in MCS", "head": ["Drug", "Mechanism", "Start dose", "Target / usual", "Key contraindication", "Monitoring"], "rows": [["Unfractionated heparin", "Antithrombin-mediated inhibition of IIa/Xa", "Bolus per protocol (e.g., 50-70 U/kg) then infusion", "aPTT/anti-Xa to device target (e.g., ECMO anti-Xa ~0.3-0.5); Impella purge often includes heparin", "Active major bleeding, HIT", "aPTT or anti-Xa, ACT (procedural), platelets (HIT), Hgb"], ["Bivalirudin (direct thrombin inhibitor)", "Direct, reversible thrombin inhibition", "~0.05-0.15 mg/kg/h infusion (no bolus for MCS anticoag)", "aPTT to target; used when HIT present or heparin resistance", "Active bleeding; cleared mainly by proteolysis with ~20% renal clearance, so dose-adjust in severe renal impairment", "aPTT, renal function, Hgb"], ["Warfarin (durable LVAD)", "Vitamin K epoxide reductase inhibition", "2.5-5 mg daily", "INR ~2.0-3.0 (HeartMate 3 typically 2.0-2.5)", "Pregnancy, active bleeding", "INR, Hgb; drug/diet interactions"], ["Aspirin (durable LVAD adjunct)", "Irreversible COX-1 platelet inhibition", "81 mg daily", "81-100 mg daily; ARIES-HM3 supports omitting aspirin in many HeartMate 3 patients on a vitamin K antagonist", "Active GI bleed, allergy", "Bleeding, Hgb"]]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "label": "Vasoactive and inotropic agents in cardiogenic shock", "head": ["Drug", "Mechanism", "Start dose", "Usual range", "Key contraindication / caution", "Major side effects / monitoring"], "rows": [["Norepinephrine", "Alpha-1 >> beta-1 agonist", "0.05 mcg/kg/min", "0.05-0.5+ mcg/kg/min", "First-line pressor in CS; caution with severe tachyarrhythmia", "Peripheral/digital ischemia, arrhythmia; MAP, lactate, extravasation"], ["Dobutamine", "Beta-1 > beta-2 agonist (inodilator)", "2.5 mcg/kg/min", "2.5-10 (up to 20) mcg/kg/min", "Can cause hypotension (beta-2 vasodilation), tachyarrhythmia", "Tachycardia, arrhythmia, hypotension; HR, rhythm, BP"], ["Milrinone", "PDE-3 inhibitor (inodilator, pulmonary vasodilator)", "0.125-0.25 mcg/kg/min (bolus often omitted)", "0.125-0.75 mcg/kg/min", "Renally cleared — accumulates in renal failure; hypotension", "Hypotension, arrhythmia; BP, renal function, useful in RV failure/PH"], ["Epinephrine", "Beta-1/beta-2/alpha agonist", "0.01-0.05 mcg/kg/min", "up to 0.5 mcg/kg/min", "Marked tachycardia, lactate rise, arrhythmia", "Lactic acidosis, arrhythmia, ischemia; lactate, HR"], ["Vasopressin", "V1 receptor vasoconstriction", "0.03 units/min (fixed)", "0.03-0.04 units/min", "Adjunct pressor; not titrated as sole agent; digital/mesenteric ischemia", "Ischemia, hyponatremia; MAP, perfusion"], ["Dopamine", "Dose-dependent DA/beta/alpha", "5 mcg/kg/min", "5-20 mcg/kg/min", "More arrhythmia and a mortality signal vs norepinephrine in CS (SOAP II) — avoid as first line", "Tachyarrhythmia; HR, rhythm"]]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "label": "Pulmonary vasodilators for RV failure / RV support", "head": ["Drug", "Mechanism", "Start / usual dose", "Key caution", "Monitoring"], "rows": [["Inhaled nitric oxide", "Selective pulmonary vasodilation (cGMP)", "20-40 ppm inhaled", "Rebound PH on abrupt withdrawal; methemoglobinemia; expensive", "Methemoglobin, NO2, wean slowly"], ["Inhaled epoprostenol (prostacyclin)", "Pulmonary vasodilation (cAMP)", "~10-50 ng/kg/min inhaled", "Systemic hypotension if it reaches circulation; platelet inhibition", "BP, platelets"], ["Milrinone", "PDE-3 inhibition (inodilator + pulmonary vasodilator)", "See inotrope table", "Systemic hypotension; renal accumulation", "BP, renal function"]]}, {"type": "callout", "depth": 2, "variant": "fellow", "text": "In the SOAP II trial, norepinephrine was associated with fewer arrhythmic events than dopamine and a mortality signal favoring norepinephrine in the cardiogenic shock subgroup, which is why norepinephrine is the first-line vasopressor in cardiogenic shock. Dobutamine is the usual first-line inotrope; milrinone is favored when pulmonary hypertension or RV failure dominates (it is a pulmonary vasodilator) but accumulates in renal dysfunction. The DOREMI trial found no significant difference between milrinone and dobutamine for the primary composite outcome in cardiogenic shock, so agent choice is individualized to physiology and side-effect profile."}, {"type": "callout", "depth": 3, "variant": "danger", "text": "<strong>Heparin-induced thrombocytopenia (HIT)</strong> is a recurring hazard on any heparin-exposed circuit. A falling platelet count (typically 5-10 days into heparin, or faster with prior exposure) with new thrombosis should trigger a 4T assessment, cessation of all heparin (including flushes and heparin-bonded circuits where feasible), and transition to a direct thrombin inhibitor such as bivalirudin or argatroban. On ECMO/Impella this is logistically demanding but essential."}]}, {"id": "bleeding-thrombosis", "title": "The Bleeding-Thrombosis Balance and Acquired von Willebrand Syndrome", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Every continuous-flow and extracorporeal device forces the clinician to walk a narrow line between circuit/pump thrombosis on one side and hemorrhage on the other. Understanding <em>why</em> these patients bleed and clot simultaneously is a defining fellowship-level concept, because the two problems frequently coexist in the same patient at the same time."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 2, "entries": [{"term": "Acquired von Willebrand syndrome (AVWS)", "def": "High shear stress across the pump unfolds von Willebrand factor and exposes it to cleavage by ADAMTS13, destroying the high-molecular-weight multimers that are most effective at primary hemostasis. The result is a bleeding diathesis analogous to type 2A von Willebrand disease, seen with essentially all continuous-flow LVADs and, to varying degrees, other high-shear pumps."}, {"term": "Angiodysplasia / arteriovenous malformations", "def": "Reduced pulse pressure (diminished pulsatility) in continuous-flow support is thought to promote GI mucosal angiodysplasia, which, combined with AVWS and anticoagulation, produces the characteristic recurrent GI bleeding of LVAD patients."}, {"term": "Consumptive coagulopathy on ECMO", "def": "The large foreign surface of the ECMO circuit consumes platelets and clotting factors and activates fibrinolysis, producing thrombocytopenia and low fibrinogen even while the patient is anticoagulated — bleeding and clotting risk rise together."}]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "label": "Bleeding vs thrombosis — the two-sided ledger", "head": ["", "Drivers of BLEEDING", "Drivers of THROMBOSIS"], "rows": [["Device-related", "AVWS (shear), platelet consumption, hemolysis, pump-related fibrinolysis", "Foreign surface, stasis (LV distension on ECMO, closed AV), low-flow states"], ["Iatrogenic", "Therapeutic anticoagulation + antiplatelet therapy, large-bore access sites", "Subtherapeutic anticoagulation, interrupted anticoagulation for procedures"], ["Patient-related", "Reduced pulsatility angiodysplasia, hepatic congestion, uremic platelet dysfunction", "HIT, malignancy, infection/inflammation, AF"], ["Clinical clue", "GI bleed, access-site oozing, epistaxis, falling Hgb without hemolysis", "Power spike (LVAD thrombosis), oxygenator dP rise, hemolysis, stroke"]]}, {"type": "callout", "depth": 3, "variant": "fellow", "text": "GI bleeding in an LVAD patient is managed by reducing (not necessarily eliminating) anticoagulation, endoscopic control, and adjuncts such as octreotide for angiodysplasia; recurrent bleeding sometimes prompts speed adjustment to modulate pulsatility. The crucial judgment is that <em>holding anticoagulation risks pump thrombosis and stroke</em>, so decisions are individualized with the VAD team rather than reflexively reversing. AVWS also means that a normal von Willebrand antigen level does not exclude a functional defect — loss of high-molecular-weight multimers is the abnormality, and it reverses after the device is removed or the heart is transplanted."}, {"type": "callout", "depth": 1, "variant": "pearl", "text": "<strong>Mnemonic — a power spike means think 'CLOT':</strong> <strong>C</strong>heck hemolysis labs (LDH, plasma-free Hgb), <strong>L</strong>ook at the ramp echo, <strong>O</strong>ptimize/intensify anticoagulation, <strong>T</strong>ransplant/exchange team if refractory. Conversely, a falling Hgb without hemolysis in a device patient means think GI angiodysplasia and AVWS."}]}, {"id": "escalation-algorithm", "title": "Escalation and Device Selection Algorithm", "body": [{"type": "steps", "depth": 1, "label": "A practical MCS escalation pathway in cardiogenic shock", "items": ["Recognize shock and activate the shock team; obtain SCAI stage, lactate, and early right-heart catheterization to phenotype (LV vs RV vs biventricular, filling pressures, CPO, PAPi).", "Optimize the basics: revascularize if ischemic (culprit-vessel PCI), treat arrhythmia, correct hypoxia/acidosis, and start first-line pharmacology (norepinephrine plus an inotrope such as dobutamine).", "If hypoperfusion persists (rising lactate, CPO <0.6 W, escalating pressors), determine the failing chamber and support needed.", "Isolated LV failure needing flow with adequate oxygenation: escalate to a microaxial flow pump (Impella CP/5.5) for direct LV unloading; reserve IABP for mechanical complications or refractory ischemia.", "Biventricular failure, or shock with respiratory failure/severe hypoxemia, or refractory arrest with a reversible cause: VA-ECMO, with an explicit plan for LV venting if the LV distends.", "Isolated RV failure refractory to medical therapy: Impella RP or ProtekDuo (oxy-RVAD if oxygenation also needed).", "Reassess continuously against the exit strategy: recovery (wean), durable LVAD candidacy (assess RV function first), transplant listing, or, when non-recoverable and not a candidate, transition to palliative goals."]}, {"type": "callout", "depth": 2, "variant": "fellow", "text": "The recurring fellowship theme across all three landmark trials (IABP-SHOCK II negative, ECLS-SHOCK negative, DanGer Shock positive for microaxial support in STEMI shock) is that <strong>a device only helps if it corrects the specific physiologic deficit and bridges to a defined endpoint</strong>, and that the complication burden of larger-bore support is real and must be actively managed. Reflexive, non-selective device placement does not improve survival; matched, protocolized, team-based support in the right phenotype does."}, {"type": "callout", "depth": 1, "variant": "pearl", "text": "<strong>Mnemonic — before every escalation, 'STOP':</strong> <strong>S</strong>tage (SCAI), <strong>T</strong>arget chamber (which ventricle), <strong>O</strong>xygenation need (ECMO if yes), <strong>P</strong>lan for exit (recovery/durable/transplant/palliation). If you cannot state the exit, reconsider escalating."}]}, {"id": "monitoring", "title": "Daily Monitoring of the MCS Patient", "body": [{"type": "list", "depth": 1, "label": "Universal MCS monitoring bundle", "items": ["Perfusion: MAP, lactate trend, urine output, mentation, mixed venous saturation, capillary refill.", "Device parameters: read the device's own numbers at least each shift (Impella P-level/flow/motor current/placement signal; ECMO flow/sweep/pre- and post-oxygenator pressures; LVAD speed/flow/power/PI).", "Access sites and limbs: distal pulses and perfusion of every cannulated limb, hematoma, bleeding, compartment signs.", "Hemolysis surveillance on high-shear pumps: plasma-free hemoglobin, LDH, haptoglobin, urine color, hematocrit.", "Anticoagulation: aPTT/anti-Xa/ACT or INR per device; daily CBC watching platelets (HIT) and hemoglobin (bleeding).", "Daily echo for LV/RV function, device position, LV distension (on ECMO), tamponade, and aortic valve behavior.", "Neurologic checks (stroke is common across all devices); infection surveillance (driveline, cannula sites)."]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "label": "Device-specific 'must-check' each shift", "head": ["Device", "Do not miss"], "rows": [["IABP", "Augmentation adequacy and timing, left arm pulse/neuro (proximal migration), platelets, distal limb, gas alarms"], ["Impella", "Placement signal + motor current pulsatility, suction alarms, purge pressure trend, hemolysis labs, limb perfusion"], ["VA-ECMO", "Right-radial SpO2/ABG (differential hypoxia), arterial pulsatility and LV distension, oxygenator dP, distal limb perfusion"], ["HeartMate 3", "Speed/flow/power/PI as a set (power spike = thrombus), Doppler MAP <90, driveline site, INR, hemolysis, RV function"]]}, {"type": "callout", "depth": 3, "variant": "fellow", "text": "The most common preventable MCS disasters are mechanical, not hemodynamic: an unrecognized ischemic cannulated limb, a migrated device, a stopped LVAD from a controller/power fault, an unnoticed hemolysis trend, and unrecognized LV distension on ECMO. A disciplined, device-specific checklist each shift catches these before they become catastrophic."}]}], "guidelines": [{"society": "ESC", "year": "2023", "cor": "III", "text": "Routine intra-aortic balloon pump is not recommended in acute MI with cardiogenic shock in the absence of a mechanical complication (reflecting IABP-SHOCK II)."}, {"society": "ACC/AHA/HFSA", "year": "2022", "cor": "2a", "text": "In carefully selected patients with advanced (stage D) heart failure refractory to guideline-directed therapy, durable mechanical circulatory support (e.g., LVAD) can be beneficial as bridge to transplant or destination therapy."}, {"society": "SCAI", "year": "2022", "text": "Classify cardiogenic shock by the staged SHOCK schema (A-E) with a cardiac-arrest modifier, reassessing stage over time to guide escalation."}, {"society": "ACC/AHA/SCAI", "year": "2021", "text": "Temporary mechanical circulatory support may be considered as a bridge in acute mechanical complications of MI (acute severe MR, post-infarction VSD) or refractory ischemia."}], "quiz": [{"stem": "A 62-year-old man with an anterior STEMI develops cardiogenic shock. He undergoes successful PCI to the LAD. He remains on norepinephrine and dobutamine with a lactate of 5.2 mmol/L and cardiac power output of 0.5 W. The team places an intra-aortic balloon pump. On the arterial waveform (1:2), the augmented diastolic peak occurs well after the dicrotic notch, and there is no reduction in the assisted aortic end-diastolic pressure. Which timing error is present, and what is its consequence?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Early inflation, causing premature aortic valve closure"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Late inflation, causing suboptimal diastolic coronary augmentation"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Early deflation, causing retrograde coronary flow"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Late deflation, causing increased afterload"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Correct timing with an adequate augmentation"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "Augmentation appearing well after the dicrotic notch indicates the balloon is inflating too late, so diastolic augmentation of coronary perfusion is suboptimal. Early inflation would push augmentation to or before the notch and risk premature aortic valve closure. Late deflation blunts the assisted systole and raises afterload (the most dangerous error). Learning to read the 1:2 tracing against the dicrotic notch is the core IABP skill. Note also that IABP-SHOCK II showed no mortality benefit for routine IABP in AMI shock, so its use here would be reserved for specific indications."}, {"stem": "A 48-year-old woman with acute myocardial infarction and cardiogenic shock has an Impella CP placed. Two hours later the nurse reports a suction alarm, the flow has fallen from 3.5 to 1.8 L/min, and the placement waveform has become damped and less pulsatile. Blood pressure is 82/60 with a CVP of 16 and echocardiographic evidence of a dilated, hypokinetic right ventricle with a small, underfilled left ventricle. What is the most appropriate next step?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Increase the Impella P-level to restore flow"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Immediately remove the Impella for malfunction"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Recognize right ventricular failure and support the RV (e.g., inotropes/Impella RP), while reducing P-level and optimizing volume"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Start aggressive diuresis to reduce the CVP"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Administer a beta-blocker to reduce myocardial oxygen demand"}], "correct": "C", "explanation": "The picture is an underfilled LV due to right ventricular failure: the RV cannot deliver blood across the lungs, so the LV (and therefore the Impella) is preload-starved, producing suction alarms and a damped placement signal. Increasing the P-level worsens suction and hemolysis. Diuresis would further reduce LV preload. The fix is to support the failing RV (inotropes such as dobutamine/milrinone, pulmonary afterload reduction, or an Impella RP/ProtekDuo) while lowering the Impella P-level and judiciously optimizing volume. This 'RV unmasked by LV support' scenario is a classic MCS trap."}, {"stem": "A 55-year-old man is on peripheral femoral-femoral VA-ECMO for fulminant myocarditis. His native cardiac function has partially recovered but he has severe pulmonary edema and poor lung compliance. His lower-extremity SpO2 reads 99%, but his right-hand SpO2 is 84%, and a right radial ABG shows PaO2 of 52 mmHg. What is the mechanism of this finding?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Oxygenator failure delivering hypoxic blood to the entire body"}, {"key": "B", "text": "North-South (Harlequin) syndrome: recovering native cardiac output ejects poorly oxygenated blood to the upper body while well-oxygenated retrograde ECMO flow perfuses the lower body"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Left ventricular distension causing pulmonary edema"}, {"key": "D", "text": "A left-to-right intracardiac shunt"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Sampling error from the arterial line"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "This is differential hypoxia (North-South or Harlequin syndrome), specific to peripheral VA-ECMO. As the native heart recovers, it ejects blood that has passed through diseased lungs (poorly oxygenated) antegrade to the upper body, including the coronaries and cerebral circulation, while the ECMO circuit's well-oxygenated blood flows retrograde up the aorta to the lower body. The mixing point migrates depending on the balance of native versus circuit flow. Because the right radial artery (and coronaries/brain) is perfused by native output, right-hand SpO2 and right radial ABG are monitored. Management includes optimizing native lung oxygenation, converting to a V-A-V hybrid, or moving arterial return more proximally (axillary/central)."}, {"stem": "A 60-year-old woman with a HeartMate 3 LVAD presents with fatigue and low-flow alarms. Device interrogation shows an unexpectedly HIGH displayed flow, a sustained rise in power from a baseline of 5 W to 9 W, and hemolysis labs reveal LDH of 1400 U/L, plasma-free hemoglobin elevation, and tea-colored urine. Which complication is most likely?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Hypovolemia"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Right ventricular failure"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Pump thrombosis"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Driveline disconnection"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Cardiac tamponade"}], "correct": "C", "explanation": "A sustained rise in power with a falsely elevated displayed flow, together with hemolysis (high LDH, elevated plasma-free hemoglobin, hemoglobinuria), is the classic signature of pump thrombosis. The displayed flow is an estimate derived from power and speed, so a clot that increases motor work inflates the flow estimate while the motor draws more power. Hypovolemia and RV failure cause LOW flow with a low pulsatility index and no power spike. Confirm with hemolysis labs and an echocardiographic ramp study; management is intensified anticoagulation or pump exchange. Although the fully magnetically levitated HeartMate 3 (MOMENTUM 3) markedly reduced thrombosis versus the axial-flow HeartMate II, it can still occur."}, {"stem": "A 58-year-old man with STEMI-related cardiogenic shock is being considered for early mechanical circulatory support. The team wants to apply the best current randomized evidence. Which statement most accurately reflects the landmark trials?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "IABP-SHOCK II demonstrated a clear 30-day mortality benefit for routine IABP in AMI shock"}, {"key": "B", "text": "ECLS-SHOCK showed that routine early VA-ECMO reduced mortality with fewer bleeding complications"}, {"key": "C", "text": "DanGer Shock showed that a microaxial flow pump reduced 180-day mortality in STEMI shock, at the cost of more complications such as bleeding, limb ischemia, and renal replacement therapy"}, {"key": "D", "text": "All three trials were uniformly positive for their respective devices"}, {"key": "E", "text": "DanGer Shock showed no benefit of the microaxial flow pump over standard care"}, {"key": "F", "text": "IABP-SHOCK II established the IABP as first-line therapy for all cardiogenic shock"}], "correct": "C", "explanation": "DanGer Shock was the first RCT to demonstrate a mortality benefit for a microaxial flow pump (Impella CP) in STEMI-related cardiogenic shock, reducing 180-day all-cause mortality but with significantly more adverse events (severe bleeding, limb ischemia, hemolysis, renal replacement therapy). By contrast, IABP-SHOCK II showed NO mortality benefit for routine IABP in AMI shock (now a Class III indication in that setting), and ECLS-SHOCK showed NO mortality benefit for routine early VA-ECMO with MORE bleeding and vascular complications. The unifying lesson: a device helps only when it corrects the specific physiologic deficit in the right phenotype and bridges to a defined endpoint, and larger-bore support carries a real complication burden."}, {"stem": "A patient on peripheral VA-ECMO for cardiogenic shock develops a progressively flat (non-pulsatile) arterial waveform, worsening pulmonary edema with a new chest radiograph 'white-out,' and echocardiography shows a dilated left ventricle with an aortic valve that no longer opens and spontaneous echo contrast ('smoke') in the LV cavity. What is the underlying problem and the appropriate management?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Oxygenator failure; replace the oxygenator"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Left ventricular distension from increased afterload; institute LV venting (e.g., Impella/'ECPELLA', IABP, atrial septostomy, or surgical vent)"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Hypovolemia; give aggressive fluid resuscitation"}, {"key": "D", "text": "North-South syndrome; move the arterial return cannula"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Cannula chatter; reduce the pump speed only"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "The retrograde aortic flow of peripheral VA-ECMO raises LV afterload. When the LV is too weak to open the aortic valve against this pressure, blood stagnates, LVEDP and LA pressure rise (pulmonary edema/white-out), and stasis promotes intracardiac thrombus (spontaneous echo contrast). Loss of arterial pulsatility signals that the LV is not ejecting. The solution is LV venting/decompression: adding an Impella ('ECPELLA'), an IABP for afterload reduction, atrial septostomy/trans-septal LA drainage, or a surgical vent; inotropes can help the LV open the valve. Replacing the oxygenator, giving fluids, or repositioning the return cannula do not address the distension."}, {"stem": "A 67-year-old man with a HeartMate 3 LVAD (INR 2.3 on warfarin plus aspirin) presents with melena and a hemoglobin drop from 11 to 7 g/dL. Hemolysis labs are normal and pump parameters (speed, flow, power, PI) are unchanged from baseline. Which mechanism best explains his bleeding, and what is the most appropriate initial management?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Pump thrombosis causing hemolytic anemia; escalate anticoagulation"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Acquired von Willebrand syndrome with GI angiodysplasia; hold/reduce anticoagulation in conjunction with the VAD team and pursue endoscopic evaluation"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Warfarin overdose alone; give high-dose vitamin K and resume full anticoagulation the next day"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Hemorrhagic stroke; obtain urgent head CT and reverse all anticoagulation permanently"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Driveline infection causing anemia of chronic disease; start antibiotics"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "Recurrent GI bleeding is one of the most common LVAD complications and results from two device-related mechanisms acting together: acquired von Willebrand syndrome (high shear cleaves the high-molecular-weight vWF multimers) and reduced-pulsatility-associated GI angiodysplasia/AV malformations, on a background of mandated anticoagulation and antiplatelet therapy. Normal hemolysis labs and unchanged pump parameters argue against pump thrombosis (which would show a power spike and hemolysis). Management is resuscitation, temporarily reducing or holding anticoagulation in careful coordination with the VAD team (balancing pump thrombosis/stroke risk), endoscopic localization and treatment, and adjuncts such as octreotide for angiodysplasia. Permanent, unilateral reversal of all anticoagulation risks pump thrombosis and stroke and is not appropriate without team input."}], "references": ["Thiele H, et al. Intraaortic Balloon Support for Myocardial Infarction with Cardiogenic Shock (IABP-SHOCK II). New England Journal of Medicine, 2012.", "Moller JE, et al. Microaxial Flow Pump or Standard Care in Infarct-Related Cardiogenic Shock (DanGer Shock). New England Journal of Medicine, 2024.", "Thiele H, et al. Extracorporeal Life Support in Infarct-Related Cardiogenic Shock (ECLS-SHOCK). New England Journal of Medicine, 2023.", "Mehra MR, et al. A Fully Magnetically Levitated Left Ventricular Assist Device — Final Report (MOMENTUM 3). New England Journal of Medicine, 2019.", "Mehra MR, et al. Aspirin and Hemocompatibility Events with a Left Ventricular Assist Device in Advanced Heart Failure (ARIES-HM3). JAMA, 2023.", "Naidu SS, et al. SCAI SHOCK Stage Classification Expert Consensus Update. Journal of the Society for Cardiovascular Angiography and Interventions / JACC, 2022.", "De Backer D, et al. Comparison of Dopamine and Norepinephrine in the Treatment of Shock (SOAP II). New England Journal of Medicine, 2010.", "Mathew R, et al. Milrinone as Compared with Dobutamine in the Treatment of Cardiogenic Shock (DOREMI). New England Journal of Medicine, 2021.", "2021 ACC/AHA/SCAI Guideline for Coronary Artery Revascularization; 2022 AHA/ACC/HFSA Guideline for the Management of Heart Failure (cardiogenic shock and durable MCS recommendations)."]};
